Lambert and Keane held talks before Celtic’s failed attempt to land their former midfielder and he will replace former assistant manager Ian Culverhouse, who was sacked last month.

His new role at Villa Park, where he will try to help the club improve on their miserable 15th place finish last season, may also be able to accommodate his role as ITV’s top pundit on Champions League nights.

Reports in Ireland have stated Keane had a formal offer in front of him from the Scottish champions but a source close to Celtic claimed: ‘Roy was not offered the job - no-one has been offered it yet. But he has ruled himself out and asked not to be considered for the position.’

